Haring vs. Basquiat

There are many reasons for the disparity in value between Haring and Basqui=
at, both of whom died around the same time. (Basquiat overdosed in 1988; Ha=
ring died of complications from AIDS in 1990.) The conventional wisdom is t=
hat Basquiat, who also painted on unconventional armatures of all sorts, ma=
de work to be sold in galleries. That was his goal. Haring=E2=80=99s missio=
n to create art for everyone meant that even once his career had skyrockete=
d aboveground, as he said in 1984, =E2=80=9C The subway is still my favorit=
e place to draw.=E2=80=9D But there could be any of a dozen other reasons w=
hy fate has left us with a $110 million Basquiat and a $5.9 million Haring =
as their respective top auction prices.

In conversations about art, imagery, and the importance of the New York gra=
ffiti scene, no one would privilege either of these artists over the
other. (Among the surviving works from that period, there is a subway drawi=
ng that shows Haring=E2=80=99s crawling babies and Basquiat=E2=80=99s signa=
ture crown.) In fact, in terms of direct impact on the art that festooned t=
he New York City subways in the 1970s, Haring is clearly the more significa=
nt figure. =E2=80=9CI arrived in New York,=E2=80=9D Haring wrote in the int=
roduction to the book documenting his subway drawings, =E2=80=9Cat a time w=
hen the most beautiful paintings being shown in the city were on wheels=E2=
=80=94on trains=E2=80=94paintings that traveled to you instead of vice vers=
a.=E2=80=9D

Haring spent two years looking at graffiti while he struggled as a young ma=
n to find his vision and voice as an artist. He tried performance; he tried=
 video; he drew inspiration from William S. Burroughs and studied semiotics=
=2E Eventually, graffiti won out. Th=
ere was, he observed, an =E2=80=9Cobvious=
 mastery of drawing and color.=E2=80=9D But what impressed Haring the most =
was =E2=80=9Cthe scale, the pop imagery, the
commitment to drawing worthy of risk and the direct relationship between ar=
tist and audience.=E2=80=9D

As much as Haring admired graffiti art, he had no intention of =E2=80=9Cjum=
ping on the band-wagon and imitating their style.=E2=80=9D Instead, he woul=
d begin to paint on tarpaulins and other objects and conceive of more ambit=
ious public projects. =E2=80=9CWith Keith, you have a world of mediums,=E2=
=80=9D Warsh told me, =E2=80=9Cwhere the sum total is, =E2=80=98Wow, this g=
uy is really smart.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D This point will be made when Crystal =
Bridges opens its exhibition, in March of 2026, in Bentonville. Keith Harin=
g in 3D, curated by Glenn Adamson, will explore the wide ambit of a groundb=
reaking artist whose last concern was making paintings for collectors.

Keith Haring, Untitled (Mermaid =E2=80=93 Angel, Dolphins, Angels, Barking =
Dogs) (c. 1981-83), estimated at $500,000

The Infinite Stream

Collectors, of course, play their own role in the career and reputation of =
an artist. Warsh, who was living downtown in the early =E2=80=9980s, became=
 obsessed with the work of Basquiat and Haring. (He would eventually sit on=
 the Basquiat authentication committee before it was disbanded.) And with b=
oth Basquiat and Haring, Warsh did not have to consider whether their work =
was important. He knew immediately that it was.

If collectors have a role in culture, it is to see the future, or=E2=80=94a=
s Warsh put it in the introduction to the catalog of the 2012 Brooklyn Muse=
um exhibition of the subway drawings=E2=80=94to =E2=80=9Crecognize, with gr=
eat clarity, that a given artwork or artist is =E2=80=A6 significant to the=
 art and culture of their time. =E2=80=A6 Collectors, with their passion fo=
r discovery and confidence in their own tastes, sometimes have a knack for =
seeing ahead
in this way.=E2=80=9D

$(ad3_title) ( https://hindmanauctions.com/auctions/2104-post-war-and-conte=
mporary-art?utm_campaign=3D2104%20Post%20War%20and%20Contemporary%20Art&utm=
_source=3DDigital%20Ad&utm_content=3DPuck%20Wall%20Power&utm_campaign=3DWal=
l+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2811%2F5%2F24%29&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io )

In fact, Warsh=E2=80=99s defiance of Haring=E2=80=99s own preference that t=
he subway drawings disappear under a palimpsest of advertising imagery is a=
lso part of what collectors do. (As Warsh put it, =E2=80=9CThey pull from t=
he infinite stream of objects and images that cross their paths.=E2=80=9D) =
What Warsh liked about the subway drawings is that they were not pristine a=
nd bear the =E2=80=9Crips and wrinkles=E2=80=9D of their origins in the dir=
ty New York of punk rock and disco. Now, 40 years later, Warsh is selling t=
he drawings to realize some value for himself after having held them for so=
 long=E2=80=94the entire group has an estimate of more than $6 million and =
is backed by a Sotheby=E2=80=99s guarantee=E2=80=94though only Warsh knows =
how much money he has spent over that time storing the works, sponsoring ex=
hibitions and catalogs, and otherwise promoting Haring=E2=80=99s legacy.

One of the
advantages of the art market and auction houses is that their sales are als=
o marketing for the value of the works that they have sold. In other words,=
 Sotheby=E2=80=99s isn=E2=80=99t simply creating a virtual subway station o=
f the era and showing archival footage of Haring at work. If the works sell=
 for numbers much higher than their estimates (and they are clearly estimat=
ed to sell), the momentum will have an impact on Haring=E2=80=99s reputatio=
n. The strong sale of so many objects from the same body of work should rai=
se interest in that body of work and the artist. Warsh would love nothing m=
ore than to see museums bidding and buying these drawings; it=E2=80=99s rea=
lly the first chance they would have to do so. And that, as far as Warsh is=
 concerned, is the best route to archiving Haring=E2=80=99s art for everyon=
e.

Endnotes=E2=80=A6

Okay, that=E2=80=99s probably more than enough for Election Night.

One last thing, though. I=E2=80=99ve heard from a couple of you about the c=
rypto community brouhaha surrounding Michael Bouhanna, Sotheby=E2=80=99s he=
ad of digital art. (See what I did there?) Before posting about the Comedia=
n (Ban) ( https://www.coingecko.com/en/coins/comedian?utm_campaign=3DWall+P=
ower+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2811%2F5%2F24%29&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io ) memecoin on=
 Sunday, I spoke to Bouhanna about his role in launching the coin, his posi=
tive tweets about Maurizio Cattelan=E2=80=99s artwork Comedian, and the fac=
t that he was behind the scenes launching the tokens for Comedian (Ban). He=
 told me he has not realized any money from the launch. And I have no evide=
nce that
casts doubt on his claim.

Around the time of our conversation, he posted a longer explanation ( https=
://x.com/michaelbouhanna/status/1853128496672919684?utm_campaign=3DWall+Pow=
er+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2811%2F5%2F24%29&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io ) on Twitter/X.=
 For reasons of space and not fully understanding much of how the crypto wo=
rld works, I decided not to include that information in my small item about=
 the tokens. (I=E2=80=99m still primarily interested in their predictive va=
lue; the current market cap is $22 million.) Others feel differently. I got=
 more than one email pointing to Bouhanna=E2=80=99s role. The criticism see=
ms to center on the fact that Bouhanna used a high-profile account to promo=
te the artwork while he was anonymously creating the tokens and sharing the=
 token with friends who appear to have spread the word. (For what it=E2=80=
=99s worth, the tokens
weren=E2=80=99t launched until after the first tweet.) According to one of =
Bouhanna=E2=80=99s critics, =E2=80=9CIt either betrays a naivet=C3=A9 about=
 how it would be perceived or an undisclosed profit motive. Both bad looks.=
=E2=80=9D

You can decide for yourself whether this is a crypto world controversy or a=
 real transgression while you wait for next week=E2=80=99s installments of =
Wall Power.

Speak to you then,
M

