         <tr class=3D"replica" name=3D"s4">
          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 16px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">There are many reas=
ons for the disparity in value between Haring and Basquiat, both of whom di=
ed around the same time. (Basquiat overdosed in 1988; Haring died of compli=
cations from AIDS in 1990.) The conventional wisdom is that Basquiat, who a=
lso painted on unconventional armatures of all sorts, made work to be sold =
in galleries. That was his goal. Haring=E2=80=99s mission to create art for=
 everyone meant that even once his career had skyrocketed aboveground, as h=
e said in 1984, =E2=80=9C The subway is still my favorite place to draw.=E2=
=80=9D But there could be any of a dozen other reasons why fate has left us=
 with a $110 million Basquiat and a $5.9 million Haring as their respective=
 top auction prices. <br/>     <br/>In conversations about art, imagery, an=
d the importance of the New York graffiti scene, no one would privilege eit=
her of these artists over the
other. (Among the surviving works from that period, there is a subway drawi=
ng that shows Haring=E2=80=99s crawling babies <i>and</i> Basquiat=E2=80=99=
s signature crown.) In fact, in terms of direct impact on the art that fest=
ooned the New York City subways in the 1970s, Haring is clearly the more si=
gnificant figure. =E2=80=9CI arrived in New York,=E2=80=9D Haring wrote in =
the introduction to the book documenting his subway drawings, =E2=80=9Cat a=
 time when the most beautiful paintings being shown in the city were on whe=
els=E2=80=94on trains=E2=80=94paintings that traveled to you instead of vic=
e versa.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>Haring spent two years looking at graffiti while=
 he struggled as a young man to find his vision and voice as an artist. He =
tried performance; he tried video; he drew inspiration from <b>William S. B=
urroughs</b> and studied semiotics. Eventually, graffiti won out. There was=
, he observed, an =E2=80=9Cobvious mastery of drawing and color.=E2=80=9D B=
ut what impressed Haring the most was =E2=80=9Cthe scale, the pop imagery, =
the
commitment to drawing worthy of risk and the direct relationship between ar=
tist and audience.=E2=80=9D<br/> <br/>As much as Haring admired graffiti ar=
t, he had no intention of =E2=80=9Cjumping on the band-wagon and imitating =
their style.=E2=80=9D Instead, he would begin to paint on tarpaulins and ot=
her objects and conceive of more ambitious public projects. =E2=80=9CWith K=
eith, you have a world of mediums,=E2=80=9D Warsh told me, =E2=80=9Cwhere t=
he sum total is, =E2=80=98Wow, this guy is really smart.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D =
This point will be made when Crystal Bridges opens its exhibition, in March=
 of 2026, in Bentonville. <i>Keith Haring in 3D, </i>curated by <b>Glenn</b=
> <b>Adamson</b>, will explore the wide ambit of a groundbreaking artist wh=
ose <i>last</i> concern was making paintings for collectors.  <br/></td>
         </tr>
