          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">In fact, Warsh=E2=
=80=99s defiance of Haring=E2=80=99s own preference that the subway drawing=
s disappear under a palimpsest of advertising imagery is also part of what =
collectors do. (As Warsh put it, =E2=80=9CThey pull from the infinite strea=
m of objects and images that cross their paths.=E2=80=9D) What Warsh liked =
about the subway drawings is that they were not pristine and bear the =E2=
=80=9Crips and wrinkles=E2=80=9D of their origins in the dirty New York of =
punk rock and disco. Now, 40 years later, Warsh is selling the drawings to =
realize some value for himself after having held them for so long=E2=80=94t=
he entire group has an estimate of more than $6 million and is backed by a =
Sotheby=E2=80=99s guarantee=E2=80=94though only Warsh knows how much money =
he has spent over that time storing the works, sponsoring exhibitions and c=
atalogs, and otherwise promoting Haring=E2=80=99s legacy. <br/><br/>One of =
the
advantages of the art market and auction houses is that their sales are als=
o marketing for the value of the works that they have sold. In other words,=
 Sotheby=E2=80=99s isn=E2=80=99t simply creating a virtual subway station o=
f the era and showing archival footage of Haring at work. If the works sell=
 for numbers much higher than their estimates (and they are clearly estimat=
ed to sell), the momentum will have an impact on Haring=E2=80=99s reputatio=
n. The strong sale of so many objects from the same body of work should rai=
se interest in that body of work and the artist. Warsh would love nothing m=
ore than to see museums bidding and buying these drawings; it=E2=80=99s rea=
lly the first chance they would have to do so. And that, as far as Warsh is=
 concerned, is the best route to archiving Haring=E2=80=99s art for everyon=
e. <br/></td>
